From e60656127a974fd0f507f6a0987adabcd9f421c8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Kol Crooks <kol.crooks@datadoghq.com>
Date: Thu, 7 May 2026 11:55:46 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] Diff view: all-or-nothing LSP upgrade to avoid mixed-content
 visual bug
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Patch 0064 upgraded each diff side independently — head to file:// when
the working tree was on the PR head, base to krt-git:// always. That
produced a mixed-content state when only one side resolved: full file
content on the upgraded side, patch-reconstructed compact text on the
other. The diff editor compared them and every line outside the patch's
hunks showed as a difference, since those lines didn't exist on the
virtual side at all. Symptom: large unrelated chunks of code visually
flagged as changed.

Fix: all-or-nothing upgrade.

- Working tree on PR head is checked first. If not, neither side
  upgrades — keeping a virtual base while head stays virtual is a no-op,
  but also avoids a half-upgrade where base goes to krt-git:// while
  head stays krt-pr-head:// (also mixed mode).
- Both sides resolve in parallel via `Promise.allSettled` so a one-
  sided rejection doesn't leak the other side's IReference. If either
  fails, both refs dispose and the constructor-mounted virtual diff
  stays in place.
- Added/removed files skip the upgrade entirely. Their virtual diff
  already shows the full content on the relevant side (the other side
  is naturally empty); LSP for those files is deferred — most code
  review traffic is modified files anyway.

When the upgrade succeeds, both sides are full content, realLines is
identity (built-in 'on' numbering), comments re-register at the new
URIs, and hideUnchangedRegions flips on. When it fails, the virtual
patch-direct rendering keeps working as before — same visual as
without this whole feature.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
